full_threads.body:
Hi WP Perk,

As you may know, obsolete versions of PHP are periodically replaced by more recent versions. It's that time again, as active support of PHP 7.3 ended late last year, and security support (patches to address security issues) are ending in early December.

So on October 12th, we will begin removing PHP 7.3 from our platform.

Any sites still using PHP 7.3 on October 12th will be automatically switched to PHP 7.4 during October or November. We cannot tell you the specific date that your sites may be switched, as the process will take several weeks to complete.

If you want to control when your sites will be switched, you can make the change for yourself before October 12th (see below).

Make sure your site is ready for the change

We strongly recommend switching your sites to PHP 7.4 yourself before the automatic change on October 12th. That way, you can check to ensure that going from PHP 7.3 to 7.4 will not break anything on your site.

While it's unlikely that the move from PHP 7.3 to 7.4 will have a negative effect, it's still best practice to test your site and plugins to be sure. You can test the changes in a staging environment and update your live site when you're satisfied that your site is working properly with the new PHP version.

Unsupported versions of PHP are a security risk

Security vulnerabilities discovered in unsupported PHP versions cannot be fixed, so live sites should no longer use those versions. That's why Kinsta removes the option to use unsupported versions.

You upgrade WordPress to ensure that your site is protected against security vulnerabilities. You should update PHP in the same way. If you want to read about some of the benefits and changes, check out our articles, What's New in PHP 7.4 and What's New in PHP 8.

There's another good reason to upgrade. More recent versions of PHP are not only safer, but they're also often faster than the versions they replace. Any time you can get an unexpected performance increase, that's a win!

How to upgrade to the latest version of PHP

Upgrading PHP versions in MyKinsta is as easy as selecting a new version from a dropdown menu. Our safe PHP upgrades guide provides step-by-step instructions.

Be aware that switching versions may break your site. We suggest using a staging environment to test the switch. That way, your live site will not be affected until you're ready to push staging to the live site.

If your site breaks after upgrading to the latest version of PHP

PHP upgrade issues usually happen when code on your site uses old functions that are no longer supported by the newer versions of PHP. Look at your plugins and the active theme. The safe PHP upgrades guide mentioned above can help you troubleshoot some of the more common upgrade issues.

We know that technology updates can be inconvenient and disruptive. But Kinsta is dedicated to providing you with the fastest and most secure website hosting environment anywhere. We want your sites to use the safest, most up-to-date technology available.

If you have any questions about the PHP version changes, we're here for you. Feel free to connect with us in MyKinsta.
The Kinsta Team
